`sv0c/` owns compiler implementation details.

## Compiler-layer discipline

When changing compiler behavior, identify which compiler layer is affected:

- lexer
- parser
- AST
- name resolution
- type checking
- contract analysis
- intermediate representation
- lowering
- C backend
- VM backend
- diagnostics
- tests

Do not make broad compiler edits without understanding which layer owns the behavior.

## Boundary rules

- do not treat compiler implementation details as the normative language definition
- do not encode speculative semantics that are not grounded in the spec
- keep parser behavior, type behavior, and lowering behavior conceptually separate
- keep diagnostics aligned with the actual enforced rule

## Backend discipline

When a change affects code generation:

- distinguish whether it affects the C backend, the VM backend, or shared lowering
- do not assume a backend-specific workaround is a language-level rule
- prefer shared semantic consistency before backend-specific special cases

## Documentation and tests

Prefer tests that prove the intended compiler behavior explicitly.

If behavior changes, update:

- relevant compiler-local docs
- related milestone/task documents when they track the affected area
- diagnostics or golden outputs if applicable

## Avoid

Do not mix unrelated cleanup with parser/type/lowering behavior changes unless clearly justified.
Do not hide semantic changes inside refactors.
Do not change diagnostics in ways that obscure what rule is actually being enforced.
